\pard\qc\b\f0\fs36 AI-Based Plant Disease Identification Application\b0\fs24\par
\pard\qc\fs20 Project Documentation\par
\pard\fs20\par
\pard\b 1. System Overview\b0\par
This project is a multilingual plant disease diagnosis web application with a Vue frontend and a FastAPI backend.\par
Farmers can upload a leaf image or enter symptom text, choose their output language, and get disease details with recommendations.\par
\par
\pard\b 2. Architecture Components and Their Use\b0\par
\par
\pard\b Frontend (Vue 3 + Vite)\b0\par
Used for farmer interaction:\par
- Upload image or enter symptom text\par
- Select output language\par
- View diagnosis results\par
- Submit feedback\par
\par
\pard\b Backend API (FastAPI)\b0\par
Used as orchestration layer:\par
- Validates requests and files\par
- Runs image inference if a trained model exists\par
- Calls LLM layer for natural language explanation\par
- Stores diagnosis and feedback data\par
- Returns response in frontend-ready JSON\par
\par
\pard\b PostgreSQL (What it is used for in this architecture)\b0\par
PostgreSQL is the persistent data store. In this system it is used to:\par
- Save diagnosis records (disease, confidence, symptoms, recommendations, language, timestamp)\par
- Save user feedback records linked to each diagnosis\par
- Support the History page and analytics\par
- Build retraining datasets from real user outcomes\par
\par
\pard\b Ollama (What it is used for in this architecture)\b0\par
Ollama is the local LLM runtime. In this system it is used to:\par
- Convert model output into farmer-friendly explanation text\par
- Generate structured treatment and preventive suggestions\par
- Keep language generation local on device/server (no mandatory cloud call)\par
- Enable model swapping (example: llama3, mistral) through configuration\par
\par
\pard\b Vision Model (PyTorch wrapper)\b0\par
Used for image classification from leaf photos:\par
- Reads uploaded image\par
- Applies preprocessing\par
- Predicts disease class and confidence\par
- Passes result to LLM layer for explanation text\par
- Can load a local trained checkpoint or bootstrap one from a pretrained Hugging Face model\par
\par
\pard\b MLflow (MLOps tracking)\b0\par
Used for operational tracking of ML behavior:\par
- Log inference parameters\par
- Log confidence and latency metrics\par
- Tag runs with diagnosis id and pipeline mode\par
- Link feedback outcomes to monitored runs\par
\par
\pard\b 3. Current Runtime Flow (Image Diagnosis)\b0\par
1. User uploads image and selects language in frontend.\par
2. Frontend sends multipart request to POST /api/v1/diagnose.\par
3. Backend validates file type and metadata.\par
4. If trained checkpoint exists, backend runs VisionModel inference.\par
5. Backend calls Ollama engine for farmer-friendly explanation and recommendations.\par
6. Backend logs run metadata to MLflow.\par
7. Backend stores diagnosis record in PostgreSQL.\par
8. Backend returns diagnosis JSON to frontend.\par
9. Frontend shows result and allows feedback submission.\par
10. Feedback is stored and associated with diagnosis for future model improvement.\par
\par
\pard\b 4. Language Handling\b0\par
The system supports multiple Indian languages in UI and result content:\par
- UI labels come from frontend translation packs\par
- Diagnosis content can be retranslated through API endpoint\par
- Results page updates when user changes language\par
\par
\pard\b 5. Step-by-Step: How to Add a Trained Model to This App\b0\par
\par
\pard\b Step 1: Put PlantVillage data in the project\b0\par
Download the PlantVillage dataset and place it in a local folder such as:\par
- data/raw/PlantVillage/\par
The script supports either of these layouts:\par
- data/raw/PlantVillage/train/<class_name>/... and data/raw/PlantVillage/val/<class_name>/...\par
- data/raw/PlantVillage/<class_name>/... for automatic 80/20 split\par
\par
\pard\b Quick alternative before training your own model\b0\par
If you do not want to train immediately, you can bootstrap a pretrained PlantVillage model from Hugging Face:\par
- python scripts/download_pretrained_model.py\par
This downloads BrandonFors/effnetv2_s_plant_disease and converts it into:\par
- models/vision/plant_disease.pt\par
Once this file exists, the backend stops using the demo diagnosis path.\par
\par
\pard\b Step 2: Run one command to train and export the checkpoint\b0\par
From the project root, run:\par
- python scripts/train_plant_disease.py --data-dir data/raw/PlantVillage\par
This command trains a classifier and exports a backend-compatible checkpoint to:\par
- models/vision/plant_disease.pt\par
The exported file includes:\par
- model_state\par
- model_name\par
- num_classes\par
- class_names\par
\par
\pard\b Step 3: Share and confirm environment settings\b0\par
The .env file is now tracked in the repository so other users can pull the repo and use the same configuration directly.\par
Confirm these values in .env:\par
- VISION_MODEL_PATH=./models/vision/plant_disease.pt\par
- LLM_API_URL=http://localhost:11434\par
- LLM_MODEL=llama3 or llama2\par
- DATABASE_URL=postgresql://...\par
Optionally set the backbone:\par
- VISION_MODEL=efficientnet_v2_s\par
\par
\pard\b Step 4: Start backend\b0\par
Run backend:\par
- uvicorn src.api.main:app --reload\par
At startup, API should auto-load checkpoint through VisionModel.load(path).\par
If no local checkpoint exists and AUTO_DOWNLOAD_PRETRAINED_MODEL=true in .env, the backend will try to download the pretrained Hugging Face model automatically and convert it to the local checkpoint format.\par
\par
\pard\b Step 5: Verify model is active\b0\par
Send a test image to /api/v1/diagnose.\par
Check response field pipeline_mode:\par
- real_vision or real_vision_llm means trained model path is active\par
- mock means checkpoint was not loaded and fallback path is running\par
\par
\pard\b Step 6: Enable LLM explanation path\b0\par
Ensure Ollama is running and model is pulled:\par
- ollama pull llama3\par
- ollama serve\par
Then restart backend.\par
\par
\pard\b Step 7: Validate end-to-end\b0\par
- Upload sample leaf image from frontend\par
- Confirm disease, confidence, recommendations, explanation are returned\par
- Switch language in results page and verify retranslation flow\par
\par
\pard\b Step 8: Persist and monitor\b0\par
- Confirm diagnosis and feedback rows are written in PostgreSQL\par
- Open MLflow UI and verify run metrics are logged\par
\par
\pard\b Step 9: Improve model continuously\b0\par
Use incorrect feedback cases as hard examples for retraining, generate a new checkpoint, replace the checkpoint file, and redeploy backend.\par
\par
\pard\b 6. MLOps in This Project\b0\par
MLOps is implemented as a practical loop:\par
1. Inference runs are logged (parameters + metrics).\par
2. User feedback is stored with diagnosis link.\par
3. Low-confidence and incorrect predictions are collected.\par
4. Model is retrained using new data.\par
5. New checkpoint is deployed and monitored again.\par
\par
\pard\b 7. Key Files\b0\par
- .env\par
- .gitignore\par
- src/api/main.py\par
- src/vision/model.py\par
- src/vision/hf_loader.py\par
- scripts/download_pretrained_model.py\par
- scripts/train_plant_disease.py\par
- src/llm/engine.py\par
- src/database/models.py\par
- frontend/src/services/api.js\par
- frontend/src/pages/DiagnosisPage.vue\par
- frontend/src/pages/Results.vue\par
\par
\pard\b 8. Conclusion\b0\par
This architecture separates UI, inference, language generation, persistence, and operations tracking.\par
PostgreSQL is used for persistent diagnosis and feedback data.\par
Ollama is used for local LLM explanation and recommendation generation.\par
The trained model can be connected by placing a compatible checkpoint and updating environment configuration, without changing frontend behavior.\par
}
